{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_0172rA9ABNvykkNjLzrkFcUi","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01Q1M4NpCoSmnf1hNpmeBpcn","name":"Read","input":{"file_path":"/Users/ivintik/dev/personal/codeharness/_bmad-output/planning-artifacts/prd-operational-excellence.md"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":8153,"cache_read_input_tokens":25781,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":8153,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":1,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_019ny8ECB7uLgXDKVNYx1sev","session_id":"e1f3df9b-d919-466e-880e-1001c8652ee8","uuid":"87036590-c200-47a2-9503-0159ef95abcc"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01Q1M4NpCoSmnf1hNpmeBpcn","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→---\n     2→stepsCompleted: ['step-01-init', 'step-02-discovery', 'step-02b-vision', 'step-02c-executive-summary', 'step-03-success', 'step-04-journeys', 'step-05-domain', 'step-06-innovation', 'step-07-project-type', 'step-08-scoping', 'step-09-functional', 'step-10-nonfunctional', 'step-11-polish', 'step-12-complete']\n     3→inputDocuments:\n     4→  - product-brief-operational-excellence-2026-03-19.md\n     5→  - prd-overhaul.md\n     6→  - architecture-overhaul.md\n     7→  - ux-design-specification.md\n     8→documentCounts:\n     9→  briefs: 1\n    10→  research: 0\n    11→  brainstorming: 0\n    12→  projectDocs: 13\n    13→workflowType: 'prd'\n    14→classification:\n    15→  projectType: developer_tool\n    16→  domain: general\n    17→  complexity: medium-high\n    18→  projectContext: brownfield\n    19→  designPhilosophy: executable-first\n    20→---\n    21→\n    22→# Product Requirements Document - codeharness Operational Excellence\n    23→\n    24→**Author:** BMad\n    25→**Date:** 2026-03-19\n    26→\n    27→## Executive Summary\n    28→\n    29→codeharness enforces that autonomous agents produce working software through real-world verification, observability enforcement, and mechanical constraints. The architecture overhaul sprint (23/25 stories done) established the module structure, unified state, and stable sprint execution.\n    30→\n    31→This sprint addresses the gap exposed during self-validation: codeharness can verify that code works, but can't verify that code is *diagnosable*. When something breaks in a project managed by codeharness, is there enough telemetry to find out why? Today the answer is \"we don't know\" — there's no measurement.\n    32→\n    33→Three capabilities close this gap:\n    34→\n    35→1. **Observability enforcement** — three layers of measurement. Static analysis scans source for log coverage. Runtime validation confirms telemetry flows during test runs. An observability coverage metric (% of code paths with telemetry) gives a trackable number, enforced like test coverage.\n    36→\n    37→2. **`codeharness audit`** — comprehensive compliance check replacing `onboard`. Runs anytime, checks everything (observability, testing, docs, verification, infrastructure), generates fix stories for gaps. `onboard` becomes an alias.\n    38→\n    39→3. **Infrastructure development guidelines** — verification Dockerfile is a project artifact with formalized rules, validated by audit. The agent maintains it during development. Eliminates the recurring \"container doesn't have the binary\" class of bugs.\n    40→\n    41→### What Makes This Special\n    42→\n    43→- **Observability as a number.** 73% means 27% of error paths are invisible. Like test coverage, but for diagnosability.\n    44→- **Continuous compliance.** Not a one-time onboard — audit runs anytime, project is always either compliant or has stories to fix it.\n    45→- **Three-layer enforcement.** Static catches missing log statements. Runtime catches silent code paths. Coverage metric tracks it over time.\n    46→\n    47→## Project Classification\n    48→\n    49→- **Project Type:** Developer tool — npm CLI + Claude Code plugin (brownfield)\n    50→- **Domain:** General software development tooling\n    51→- **Complexity:** Medium-High\n    52→- **Context:** Extends existing codeharness with new audit and observability capabilities\n    53→\n    54→## Success Criteria\n    55→\n    56→### User Success\n    57→\n    58→- **Observability has a number.** Every project gets an observability coverage % from `codeharness audit`.\n    59→- **Audit is instant.** `codeharness audit` returns full compliance report in <30 seconds.\n    60→- **Gaps become stories.** `codeharness audit --fix` generates implementable stories for every gap.\n    61→- **Infrastructure stays correct.** Zero \"container missing binary\" failures when Dockerfile is a maintained project artifact.\n    62→\n    63→### Technical Success\n    64→\n    65→- **Static analysis detects missing logs.** Scans source, flags error handlers without log statements, flags functions without entry logging at debug level.\n    66→- **Runtime validation confirms data flows.** After test runs, telemetry exists in Victoria/OpenSearch for exercised code paths.\n    67→- **Coverage metric is accurate.** Observability coverage % correlates with actual diagnosability.\n    68→\n    69→### Measurable Outcomes\n    70→\n    71→| Metric | Target |\n    72→|--------|--------|\n    73→| Observability coverage metric exists | Yes — every audit produces a % |\n    74→| Audit covers all dimensions | Observability + testing + docs + verification + infra |\n    75→| Audit runtime | <30 seconds |\n    76→| Audit --fix generates stories | Stories with ACs for each gap |\n    77→| Infrastructure audit catches Dockerfile drift | Before verification fails |\n    78→| Static analysis flags per code review | Missing logs flagged during review |\n    79→\n    80→## Product Scope\n    81→\n    82→### MVP\n    83→\n    84→1. Observability static analysis (scan, count, coverage %)\n    85→2. Observability runtime validation (test run → telemetry check)\n    86→3. Observability coverage metric (configurable target, hook enforcement)\n    87→4. `codeharness audit` command (replaces onboard, all dimensions)\n    88→5. Infrastructure guidelines & Dockerfile validation\n    89→6. Observability enforcement in dev/review workflows\n    90→\n    91→### Out of Scope\n    92→\n    93→- Custom observability backends beyond Victoria*/OpenSearch\n    94→- APM dashboards\n    95→- Log aggregation or alerting rules\n    96→- Distributed tracing visualization\n    97→\n    98→## Functional Requirements\n    99→\n   100→### Observability Static Analysis\n   101→\n   102→- **FR1:** System can scan project source files and count log/trace/metric statements per function.\n   103→- **FR2:** System can identify error handlers (catch blocks, error callbacks) without log statements and flag them as observability gaps.\n   104→- **FR3:** System can classify log statements by level (debug, info, warn, error) and report the distribution.\n   105→- **FR4:** System can compute observability coverage as: (functions with at least one log statement / total functions) × 100.\n   106→- **FR5:** System supports configurable observability coverage target (default 80%).\n   107→\n   108→### Observability Runtime Validation\n   109→\n   110→- **FR6:** During black-box verification, verifier queries observability backend after each `docker exec` command to check if log events were emitted.\n   111→- **FR7:** If a user interaction (docker exec command) produces zero log events, verifier flags it as `[OBSERVABILITY GAP]` in the proof document.\n   112→- **FR8:** Runtime observability coverage = (ACs with at least one log event / total ACs verified) × 100. Reported in proof and audit.\n   113→- **FR9:** For standalone runtime check (outside verification), system can run tests with OTLP enabled and query backend for module-level telemetry.\n   114→\n   115→### Observability Coverage Metric\n   116→\n   117→- **FR10:** System reports static coverage and runtime coverage as separate numbers — not combined.\n   118→- **FR11:** System enforces observability coverage target via hooks — blocks commits below target.\n   119→- **FR12:** System tracks observability coverage trend over time in state file.\n   120→\n   121→### Audit Command\n   122→\n   123→- **FR13:** Operator can run `codeharness audit` to get a full compliance report covering: observability, testing, documentation, verification, infrastructure.\n   124→- **FR14:** Each audit dimension produces a status (pass/fail/warn) and a metric (% or grade).\n   125→- **FR15:** Operator can run `codeharness audit --fix` to generate epics/stories for all gaps found.\n   126→- **FR16:** `onboard` command becomes an alias for `audit` — same functionality, backward compatible.\n   127→- **FR17:** Audit checks verification Dockerfile exists, builds successfully, and contains required tools.\n   128→- **FR18:** Audit checks Docker observability stack health (shared or remote).\n   129→- **FR19:** Audit checks test coverage meets project target.\n   130→- **FR20:** Audit checks documentation freshness (AGENTS.md, README, exec-plans).\n   131→- **FR21:** Audit reports all results in a single structured output (human-readable and --json).\n   132→\n   133→### Infrastructure Guidelines & Validation\n   134→\n   135→- **FR22:** System provides a Dockerfile template as a starting point based on detected project type.\n   136→- **FR23:** System defines formalized rules for verification Dockerfiles: must include project binary, verification tools, no source code, proper cleanup.\n   137→- **FR24:** Audit validates the project's Dockerfile against the formalized rules and reports non-compliance.\n   138→- **FR25:** When a story adds new dependencies, the dev workflow prompts the agent to update the Dockerfile.\n   139→\n   140→### Observability Enforcement in Workflows\n   141→\n   142→- **FR26:** During code review, static analysis results are included — missing log statements flagged as review issues.\n   143→- **FR27:** During verification, runtime validation runs — observability gaps reported in proof document.\n   144→- **FR28:** Patches for dev and review workflows updated with observability enforcement rules.\n   145→\n   146→## Non-Functional Requirements\n   147→\n   148→- **NFR1:** Audit completes in <30 seconds for projects up to 100K lines of code.\n   149→- **NFR2:** Static analysis supports Node.js/TypeScript and Python source files.\n   150→- **NFR3:** Runtime validation works with both VictoriaMetrics and OpenSearch backends.\n   151→- **NFR4:** Observability coverage metric is stored in state file alongside test coverage.\n   152→- **NFR5:** Audit output follows the UX spec format (structured sections, status prefixes, actionable remedies).\n   153→- **NFR6:** Generated stories from `audit --fix` follow the BMAD story format with Given/When/Then ACs.\n   154→- **NFR7:** Infrastructure guidelines are stored as markdown in `patches/infra/` — editable without rebuilding.\n   155→- **NFR8:** All new code has 100% test coverage.\n   156→- **NFR9:** No source file exceeds 300 lines.\n   157→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_019ny8ECB7uLgXDKVNYx1sev","session_id":"e1f3df9b-d919-466e-880e-1001c8652ee8","uuid":"7c8974fe-f887-4da3-87eb-8dd98605334e","timestamp":"2026-03-20T08:37:11.208Z"}
